SIMPLE: fair
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fair
<hw>Fair</hw> <pr>(f⟦acir⟧r)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Fairer</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Fairest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>fair</ets>, <ets>fayer</ets>, <ets>fager</ets>, AS.
<ets>f⟦ae⟧ger</ets>; akin to OS. & OHG. <ets>fagar</ets>, Icel.
<ets>fagr</ets>, Sw. <ets>fager</ets>, Dan. <ets>faver</ets>, Goth.
<ets>fagrs</ets> fit, also to E. <ets>fay</ets>, G.
<ets>f⟦uum⟧gen</ets>, to fit. <ets>fegen</ets> to sweep, cleanse, and
prob. also to E. <ets>fang</ets>, <ets>peace</ets>, <ets>pact</ets>, Cf.
<er>Fang</er>, <er>Fain</er>, <er>Fay</er> to fit.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Free from spots, specks, dirt, or imperfection; unblemished; clean;
pure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>fair</qex> white linen cloth.</q> <rj><qau>Book of Common
Prayer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pleasing to the eye; handsome; beautiful.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who can not see many a <qex>fair</qex> French city, for one
<qex>fair</qex> French made.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Without a dark hue; light; clear; <as>as, a
<ex>fair</ex> skin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The northern people large and <qex>fair</qex>-complexioned.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir M. Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not overcast; cloudless; clear; pleasant;
propitious; favorable; -- said of the sky, weather, or wind, etc.;
<as>as, a <ex>fair</ex> sky; a <ex>fair</ex> day.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You wish <qex>fair</qex> winds may waft him over.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Free from obstacles or hindrances; unobstructed;
unincumbered; open; direct; -- said of a road, passage, etc.; <as>as, a
<ex>fair</ex> mark; in <ex>fair</ex> sight; a <ex>fair</ex>
view.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The caliphs obtained a mighty empire, which was in a
<xex>fair</xex> way to have enlarged.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld> <def>Without sudden change of
direction or curvature; smooth; flowing; -- said of the figure of a
vessel, and of surfaces, water lines, and other lines.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Characterized by frankness, honesty, impartiality,
or candor; open; upright; free from suspicion or bias; equitable; just;
-- said of persons, character, or conduct; <as>as, a <ex>fair</ex> man;
<ex>fair</ex> dealing; a <ex>fair</ex> statement.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧I
would call it <xex>fair</xex> play.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Pleasing; favorable; inspiring hope and confidence;
-- said of words, promises, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When <qex>fair</qex> words and good counsel will not prevail on
us, we must be frighted into our duty.</q> <rj><qau>L'
Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Distinct; legible; <as>as, <ex>fair</ex>
handwriting</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Free from any marked characteristic; average;
middling; <as>as, a <ex>fair</ex> specimen</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The news is very <qex>fair</qex> and good, my lord.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fair ball</b></col>. <fld>(Baseball)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>A ball passing over the home base at the height called for by the
batsman, and delivered by the pitcher while wholly within the lines of
his position and facing the batsman.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A batted ball
that falls inside the foul lines; -- called also a <altname>fair
hit</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Fair maid</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The European pilchard (<spn>Clupea pilchardus</spn>)
when dried.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The southern scup (<spn>Stenotomus
Gardeni</spn>).</cd> <mark>[Virginia]</mark> -- <col><b>Fair
one</b></col>, <cd>a handsome woman; a beauty,</cd> -- <col><b>Fair
play</b></col>, <cd>equitable or impartial treatment; a fair or equal
chance; justice.</cd> -- <col><b>From fair to middling</b></col>,
<cd>passable; tolerable.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>The fair
sex</b></col>, <cd>the female sex.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Candid; open; frank; ingenuous; clear; honest;
equitable; impartial; reasonable. See <er>Candid</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fair</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fair
<hw>Fair</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Clearly; openly; frankly; civilly;
honestly; favorably; auspiciously; agreeably.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fair and square</b></col>, <cd>justly; honestly;
equitably; impartially.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>To bid
fair</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Bid</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To speak
fair</b></col>, <cd>to address with courtesy and frankness.</cd>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fair</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fair
<hw>Fair</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Fairness, beauty.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A fair woman; a sweetheart.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have found out a gift for my <qex>fair</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shenstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Good fortune; good luck.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now <qex>fair</qex> befall thee !</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The fair</b></col>, <cd>anything beautiful; women,
collectively.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧For slander's mark was ever yet <xex>the
fair</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fair</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fair
<hw>Fair</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make fair or
beautiful.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Fairing</qex> the foul.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld> <def>To make smooth and
flowing, as a vessel's lines.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fair</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Fair
<hw>Fair</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>feire</ets>, OF.
<ets>feire</ets>, F. <ets>foire</ets>, fr. L. <ets>fariae</ets>, pl.,
days of rest, holidays, festivals, akin to <ets>festus</ets> festal. See
<er>Feast</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A gathering of buyers and
sellers, assembled at a particular place with their merchandise at a
stated or regular season, or by special appointment, for
trade.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A festival, and sale of fancy articles. erc.,
usually for some charitable object; <as>as, a Grand Army <ex>fair</ex>;
a church <ex>fair</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A competitive exhibition of wares, farm products,
etc., not primarily for purposes of sale; <as>as, the Mechanics'
<ex>fair</ex>; an agricultural <ex>fair</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>an exhibition by a number of organizations,
including governmental organizations, for the purpose of acquainting
people with such organizations or their members, not primarily for
commercial purposes; <as>as, the 1939 World's
<ex>Fair</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Meet me in St. Louis, Louis⟦br⟧
Meet me at the <qex>fair</qex>⟦br⟧
Don't tell me the lights are shining⟦br⟧
Anyplace but there.</q> <rj><qau>Song (1904: words by Andrew B.
Sterling, music by Kerry Mills, popularized by Billy Murray. Prominent
in the movie "Meet Me In St. Louis", 1944)</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>After the fair</b></col>, <cd>Too late.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>fair and square</ent>⟦br⟧
